'''Kia McNeill''' (born May 15, 1986) is an [[United States|American]] professional [[association football|soccer]] [[defender (association football)|defender]] currently playing for the [[Boston Breakers]] in the [[National Women's Soccer League|NWSL]]. She previously played for the [[Saint Louis Athletica]], [[Philadelphia Independence]], and the [[Atlanta Beat (WPS)|Atlanta Beat]] in the [[Women's Professional Soccer|WPS]] and was a member of the [[United States U-23 women's national soccer team]].

==Early life==
McNeill was born and grew up in [[Avon, Connecticut]] and attended [[Avon High School (Connecticut)|Avon High School]]. At Avon, she helped lead the women's soccer team to three straight Class M State Championships and three undefeated seasons. She was named 2003 State Player of the Year in Connecticut and was a two-time NSCAA High School All-American. She also earned letters in basketball and track.<ref name=wps_bio /> 

===Boston College===
McNeill was a four-year starter and played in 86 consecutive games at [[Boston College]]. She was a forward for her first three seasons and switched her senior season to defender. As a team captain, McNeill was considered crucial to the Eagles defense as it was ranked sixth in the country in goals-against-average (0.475). She finished her career as the eighth all-time leading scorer at Boston with 61 career points.<ref name=bc_bio>{{cite web|title=Kia McNeill assistant coach profile|url=http://www.bceagles.com/sports/w-soccer/mtt/kia_mcneill_249778.html|publisher=Boston College|accessdate=6 February 2013}}</ref> Her final collegiate statistics included 86 games played, 24 goals and 13 assists. McNeill was named Big East Rookie of the Year and earned All-Big East First Team selection honors. She was also named by Soccer Buzz Magazine as the Northeast Freshman of the Year.<ref name=wps_bio />

==Playing career==
===Club===
====Kristianstads DFF====
Two days after graduation at [[Boston College]], McNeill flew to Sweden to begin her professional career as a member [[Kristianstads DFF]] in the [[Damallsvenskan]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Kia McNeill Signs With Kristianstad|url=http://www.bceagles.com/sports/w-soccer/spec-rel/041008aaa.html|publisher=Boston College|accessdate=6 February 2013}}</ref>

====St. Louis Athletica====
McNeill was the ninth overall draft pick during the [[2009 WPS Draft]] by the [[Saint Louis Athletica]]. During the [[2009 Women's Professional Soccer season|2009 WPS season]], she appeared in 19 games for the [[Saint Louis Athletica]], starting 17 times. She helped anchor a Saint Louis defense that allowed the second fewest goals in the [[Women's Professional Soccer|WPS]], the second least goals against average, and the second most shutouts.<ref name=wps_bio>{{cite web|title=Kia McNeill player profile|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20120304035803/http://www.womensprosoccer.com/philadelphia/players/bios/kia-mcneill|publisher=Philadelphia Independence|accessdate=6 February 2013}}</ref>

====Atlanta Beat (WPS)====
In February 2010, McNeill was traded to the [[Atlanta Beat (WPS)|Atlanta Beat]]. She started all 19 games playing a total of 1624 minutes.<ref name=wps_bio />

====Philadelphia Independence (WPS)====
During the [[2011 WPS season]], McNeill played for the expansion team, [[Philadelphia Independence]]. She started 17 of 17 games for a total of 1453 minutes and scored one goal.<ref name=wps_bio />

====Rossiyanka====
After the WPS suspended operations in early 2012, McNeill made a small stint with [[Leigh Ann Robinson]], [[Yael Averbuch]], and [[Omolyn Davis]] playing for [[WFC Rossiyanka]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Russian Nightmares: Four former WPS players leave clubs abroad following contract disputes|url=http://equalizersoccer.com/2012/05/02/russian-nightmares-four-former-wps-players-leave-clubs-abroad-following-contract-disputes/|publisher=Equalizer Soccer|accessdate=6 February 2013}}</ref> She made one appearance, starting and playing the full ninety minutes.<ref name=soccerway>{{cite web|title=Kia McNeill player profile|url=http://int.women.soccerway.com/players/kia-mcneill/76191/|publisher=Soccer Way|accessdate=6 February 2013}}</ref>

====Boston Breakers (NWSL)====
In February 2013, it was announced that McNeill had signed with the [[Boston Breakers]] for the inaugural season of the [[National Women's Soccer League]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Breakers add defensive depth with Kia McNeill|url=http://equalizersoccer.com/2013/02/06/breakers-add-defensive-depth-with-kia-mcneill/|publisher=Equalizer Soccer|accessdate=6 February 2013}}</ref> 

===International===
McNeill appeared in two matches for the US U-23 Women's National Team in La Manga, Spain. She was previously part of the U-19 Women's national team player pool
and scored four goals for the U-19 WNT at the World Cup Qualifying Tournament in Canada.<ref name=wps_bio />

